I disagree with this.  Fusion could be far more efficient and far more abundant than most of those other power generation sources you mentioned.  I don't really understand some of the violent sentiments against it considering that it won't cause meltdowns, it leaves practically no nuclear waste (and none whatsoever if the right elements are used), and it really isn't suitable for the production of bomb-grade materials.  And I'd really rather there be a few inconspicous fusion plants in existence than to have our oceans and mountain tops clogged with energy generating equipment.  It's also strange to me that these same prophets who speak doom and gloom that in 50 years we will have used up all of our power generation resources are the same people who fanatically fight any progress in the fields of nuclear power generation.  If we switched to fuel cells for transportation and fusion/fission for energy we could go a long way toward sustaining our energy requirements and cleaning up the environment!  Of course fusion isn't practical yet but if the  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/omb/budget/fy2002/bud04.html">gov't</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> would give it more funding than a single space shuttle launch per year we'd probably have already gone a long way toward making it a reality.<br>
